{"/service/ndnp/mohi/batch_mohi_eadweard_ver01/data/sn90061783/00200292169/1913092501/1373.xml":{"full_text":"The Republican\n(Successor to The Democrat.)\nV. w. KINLOCH, Proprietor.\nDBATKICK KINLOCH,\nlxral Editor and Business Manager.\nKntered in the Tost Office at Versailles\nMissouri as second class mail matter.\nmcnt offering 50 cents discount for\ncash but did not hear from the con\ncern, so decided it was a fraud and\ncut it out. Hope all the other fellows\ngot their pay, but doubt it.\nSubscription Price, f 1.1)0 a Year,\n'Phone No. 185'\nAdvertising Rates.\nJliplay advertising, by the year, to average\nfour Inches or more, 8ftc. per Inch each lasue.\nProfessional cards, one Inch, 50 centa per\nmonth; two I lichen. 75 centa per month.\nlocals five line, or over, j centa per line for\nDrat Insertion; S He. per line for each stiheeiiuent\nInsertion. In black type 10 centa per line for\nHrt insertion, 5 cents per line for each subse\nquent insertion.\n.egal advertising t legal ratea.\nspecial ratea on page advertisements.\nREMEMBER\nto keep your subscription within the\ntwelve month's limit the post office\ndepartment says you are an outlaw, a\ndishonest person, and not to be\ntrusted when you get twelve months\nbehind. Keep on the inside.\nIt seems to be the concenses of\nopinion of reasonable minded peo\npic that Roosevelt will be a candidate\nfor President in 1910, but not a can\ndidate of the Standpatters. He will\nbe elected.\nThe Globe-Democrat and Kansas\nCity Journal apparently gloat more\nover what they are pleased to term\nthe demise of the Progressive Party\nthan they do over the hope of defeat\ning the Democrats. The venon is\nthere and they haven't sense enough\nto hide it. liourbons!\nTne Standpatters are patting them\nselves over the recent wonderful vie\ntory in Maine. You have read of\nthe drowning man and the straw.\nThere is not so much danger from\nfire now as when everything was so\ndry, but the danger is always there,\nand the fire drill practice should be\nkept up.\nHouchen, of Jefierson City, ex\npects to knock Shackleford off the\ndump. Mr. Houchen better consult\nwith Omar I). Gray, of Sturgeon, in\nregard to making the race against\naliack.\nYes, we found one kicker on the\nrain, Ed Williams, last Friday, he\ndeclared that if it didn't let up rain\ning all the corn and fodder would\nrot. Under the circumstances what\ncould we do but assure him that the\nrain was over and we would have\nfine weath :r. He left us seemingly\nin better spirits and with unabated\nfaith in what a newspaper man is\nsupposed to know. Do you remem\nber how it rained Friday evening?\nJohn McClanahan thinks his chanc\nes for the county clerkship are good\nas he is the only candidate he hears\nof who has any hope of a nomina'\nnation.\nIf we wanted to be a candidate\nfor a county office in Morgan county\nnext year we would change our resi\ndence to Stover, Florence or Syra\ncuse. It will be a slaughter of the\nVersailles \"Inooccnts.\"\nNot being able to get around to\nask questions we know little about\ncounty politics, but understand the\npot is beginning to simmer. It is\nrumored that Chas. Goodman of\nStover, W. J. Williams, foreman of\nthe Leader office, Chas. E. Willson\nand Fred Monsess will be candidates\nfor collector on the Republican tick\net, while McClelland and Agee will\ncontend for the office of prosecuting\nattorney. There will likely be a\nplenty for each office before the sea\nson is greatly advancetl.\nWonder how our exchanges came\noi'l on the Motor Cycle ad? We\ntried stu issue or two, sent in state-\nLooK Out.\nWe have contracted to print the\nMinutes for the Central Haptist Asso\nciation, a big job, and arc at work\non a telebhone directory for the Far\nmers Telephone Co., and unless the\nbnss can help do the work there will\nbe no paper during October. We\nhope to be able to do all the job\nprinting that comes our way, and get\nout some sort of paper, and by the\npaper you get you may know how\nthe editor is feeling.\nIf you are paid in advance you need\nnot fret or worry, we will move you\nup all you miss.\nMoose Want No Company.\nWashington, Sept. 18 Returning\ndirect fr m a conferencewith Colonel\nRoosevelt, Representptive Hinebaugh\nof Illinois landed a knockout punch\ntoday on those statesmen who have\nbeen talking amalgamation of the Pro\ngressive and Republican parties.\nMr. Hinebaugh bore with him Col\nonel Roosevelt's official approval of\nthe organization of a Progressive con\ngressional campaign committee effect\ned on Monday. He brought, also, a\nstatement from the Colonel urging\nthe Progressives to wage the hardest\nkind of a fight in the First Congress\nional District of West Virginia, where\nan election is to be held next month\nMr. Hinebaugh also brought a\npromise from the Colonel that if he\nis in this country during the congress\nional campaign next year he will offer\nhis time and services to the newly\ncreated congressional campaign com\nmittee. He brought, also, a promise\nof the heartiest co-operation between\nthe national and congreesional Pro\ngressive committees.\nIf there is a person in the United\nStates who has now a doubt as to the\nfuture course of the Progressive party\nand its chief, Representave Hinebaugh\nis willing to remove that doubt im\nmediately.\nMr. Hinebaugh went to New York\nat the request of Colonel Roosevelt\nand while there he conferredwith the\nformer President and other leaders\nof the parties. He did not know be\nfore leaving Washington what Colonel\nRoosevelt would say about the or\nganization of the Progressive congress\nional campagin commettee. He was\nhighly elated to return with the full\nand hearty indorsement of that com\nmittee by the former President.\n\"Mr. Roosevelt,\" Representative\nHinebaugh said, \"was enthusiastic\nand hopeful. He immensely pleased\nwith the organization of the congress\nional campaign commettee on Mon\nday and he urged us to plan for the\nstrongest sort of a fight in the con\ngressional campaign of 1014. He\nurged a strong fight in West Virginia,\nwhere there is to be an election next\nmonth.\"\nProsperty Home A Rain.\nWhen the election campaigners\nreach that stage when they know and\neveryone else knows the voters have\nall made up their minds how they\nwill mark their ballots, the campaign\ners don't stop. Thev keep on cam\npaigning. The impetus of habit\nbears them along to the very hour\nthat the polls are closed.\nSince the pulses calmed down\nafter the panic of 1907, the business\nmen of America have been campaign\ning for a return of prosperty. They\nhave written about it, lectured about\nit, organized associations for drum\nming up confidence. Now, as a\nmatter of fact, prosperity opened the\ndoor and took her accustomed place\nat the table many months ago. Yet\nthe drumming has not ceased. Hab\nit keeps business men from talking\nabout the return of prosperity as if\nshe stiil remained pouting and un-\npleased.\nThe New York Times hat grown\nimpati'nt with this needless crying\nfor something that those crying al\nready have. It asks: \"What accum\nulation of facts will convince those\ndespairing for prosperity that pros\nperity is here and gives no sign of\ndeparting despite the worst that can\nbe done by the managers of our af\nfairs?.\" The Times then proceeds\nto recite some of the facts the un\nprecedented foreign trade, the apa\nthy of the country toward the disturb\nances the changes in the tariff will\ncreate, the availability of capital\nwhen no one knows what the new\ncurrency law may do to the banking\nindustry, fhe stolidity of business in\nthe face of news of damage to the\ncrops, the tremendous increase in\nthe gross earnings of the railroads\nand the marked increase in dividend\ndisbursements.\nThough the Times is irritated\nwith the well-intentional persons who\nwon't quit begging prosperity to\ncome back home, though she's been\nhome these many months, it's noth\ning to take deeply to heart. If those\nwhose eyes are keen have observed\nthe return, even the blindest will\nlearn of it in time. Toledo Hlade.\nState Fair features.\nAa the time draws near for the\nThirteenth Annual Missouri State\nFair the patriotic feeling of Missour\nians is inducing them to bend every\neffort for its success.\nFollowing in the trail of the Im\nplement Dealers and Editor, the\nReal Estate men of Missouri have de\ncided to come to the State Fair city\nto form their state organization. H\nA. Spencer, publisher of the \"Real\nEstate Bulletin,\" Kansas City, has\nissued call for a meeting at the court\nhouse in Sedalia, Tuesday evening,\nto perfect the organization, Over a\nthousand dealers have been invited\nto be present and combine a trip to\nthe Rlue Ribbon Fair with this for\nward step for the real estate business\nin Missouri.\nThe Missouri Checker Association\nhas also arranged to holrl its first an\nnual championship tournament under\nthe auspices of the Fair. The match\nes, which will be played in the Art\nHall, will last throughout the week\nand several noted players will take\npart. Among them will be Har\nry Leiberman, juvenile champion\nof the world and Professor P. B.\nPerry, the live wire of the Missouri\nAssociation.\nAmong the attractive features ol\nthe liig Fair the Art ShowsUnds out\nas one of the best. Dr. John Pick\nard has assembled in the beautiful\nhalls of the Woman's Building the\nlargest and finest exhibition of Mis\nsouri art ever gathered together. All\nof the leading artists of the state have\ncontributed to this wonderful collec\ntion which is far above any ever\nshown on any state fair grounds.\nPaintings, etchings, wood carving\nantl statuary, grand beyond words,\noccupy every inch of available space.\nAs novel as the art show is beauti\nful and grand, is the coursing meet to\ntake place on the mile race course\nimmediately after the running races\non the afternoon of Governor's Day,\nThursday. All fox and wolf dogs\nowned by Missouriaas are c'igible\nand no entry fee is charged for the\nrace which is to be one mile. Five\nprizes are offered for the event and\nfour well known authorities on fox\nchases will act as judge. It will\nbring up thoughts of the old days\nwhen the rich tones sent up by the\npack reverbrate through the October\nair,\nThis State Fair At Sedaliu, Septem\nber 27-October 3, is Miisourian in\nevery fibre, so your Missouri patriot\nism bids you to be there.\nTruitae'i Sal.\nWhiiiai. Thomaa Kdward Wllaon. a widow\ner, by hia certain deed of trust, dated the\nseventeenth day of August, one thousand nine\nhundred and twelve, and recorded In the office\nof the Recorder of Deeds of Morgan County,\nMissouri, in book 26 at page 607, conveyed to\nthe undersigned, Edgar I'. Varnell, aa trustee,\nnil of hia right, title, interest and estate In and\ntome loiiowwc aescribea real eaiate aituaieu\nin the County of Morgan, State of Missouri, to\nwit: All of the north half of the northwest\nquarter of section twenty-five (25), of township\nfortv-two (42), of range eighteen (18), contain\ning eighty acrea. more or less, whlah said con\nveyance was made in trust to secure the pay\nment of one certain promissory note In aaM\ndeed described, and whereas the annual interest\non aaid note is due and remains unpaid, and\nwnereas ii ta provided in said need or trust mat\nthe whole shall become due and payable upon de\nfault in the payment of any part uf aaid debt\nand Interest. Now, therefore, in accordance\nwunine provissions 01 said need or tru si, and\nat the request of the legal holder of said note,\nhe havitia! elected to collect the whole nf said\ndebt and interest, I will proceed to sell the\nabove described real estate at the Court House\ndoor, in the city of Versailles, in the ciunty of\nMorgan, State of Missouri, at public vendue, to\nthe highest bidder, for cash In hand, on Tues\nday, th thirtieth day of September, A. D, 1913.\nbetween the hours of nine o'clock in the fore\nnoon and five o'clock in the afternoon of that\nday, to satisfy aaid debt and interest, together\nwith the cost and exDenses of eieculinir this\ntrust.\nDated September 4th, 1913\nKdoab p. yarnrli.. Trustee.\nDIRECTORY.\nTiara or boldisu couai,\nCircuit court-3rd Monday In April and 2nd Mori\nlay In August and December.\nProbate court 2nd Monday In February, May and\nNovember, and Mb Monday In August.\nCounty court Klrat Monday In February, Stay\nAugust and November,\nj. w. mcclelland,\nAbstracter,\nReal Estate,\nLoans and\nInsurance.\nRoom 6, Mason Hardy Bldg.\nVersailles, Mo.\nCondensed Official Report ot the\nCondition of\nThe Bank of Versailles\nMade by a Committee of Stockholders\nat the close of business Sept. 14, 1912:\nRESOURCES\nIxans and Discounts, 248,334 '37\nBonds, 1,000.00\nReal Estate, 8,180.80\nFurniture and Fixtures, 3,000.00\nCash and due from Banks 70,025.91\nTotal, $330,550.08\nLIABILITIES\nCapital Stock, full paid 30,000.00\nSURPLUS 46,723.50\nBills Payable and Redis\ncounts 37,9000.00\nDEPOSITS 215,926.58\nTotal, $330,550.08\nThe Above Statement is correct.\nWin. L. Stephens, Cashier.\nD. L. WILLIAMS\nTHE DENTIST.\nOffice in New Odd Fellow Huildiiig\nRooms 3fi..T6\nVersailles, Mo.\nPrompt service and first-class work\nto all patrons. Photic 37.\nJOHN WASSUNG.\nDEALER IN\nHarness.\nSaddles.\nBridles and\nSaddlery Hardware.\nCarriage Trimming and Re\npairing Neatly and promptly\nDone.\nIn Business 41 tears.\nHarness, Bridles, Etc.,\nHome-made, Hand-made\nand guarranteed.\nWill meet all competition\nin prices considering quality\nof material and workmanship\nCall and see me before\nbuying.\nVersailles. M ss.xiri.\nMoaiisx County\nRepresentative,\nPresiding Judge J.\nJudge 1st District\nJudge Hud District\nJudge of Probata\nCircuit Clerk and Kecorder\nCounty Clerk\nPriMucutlng Attorney\nSheriff\nCollector\nAssessor\nTreasurer\nCoroner\nPublic Administrator\nSurveyor\nSuperintendent of Schools\nOrncitu\nJ. w. KsurrusN\nW,T. Boa en\nD. A, Falrley\nAug, Scbupp\nI. M. Bctianiiep\nJohn J. Jones